topic.title: Revision 5.0

body.p: Revision 5.0 was published in November 2019. The following is a summary of the changes.

li.p: Changed all references of Hummingbird to HB20.
Updated mode-specific schematics and external component table to include the optional 32.768 kHz crystal oscillator capacitor components in Functional Descriptions.
Updated the usable core 0 and core 1 DCCM memory in the CPU Complex to reflect the availability of retention SRAM and X-Y SRAM.
Updated the SPI slave maximum clock rate to 8 MHz in Peripherals.
Added Service Mode section and clarified brown-out event mask in Supply Monitoring section.

Removed the BOR circuit references from the datasheet. The BOR circuit is redundant as supply voltages that drop below the BOR level trigger the POR circuit when returning to the normal operating voltage.
Added storage temperature range to Absolute Maximum Ratings table.
Changed the minimum VBATT supply voltage from 0.9 V to 0.92 V throughout Electrical Specifications.

Updated the RX sensitivity numbers in RF RX Performance Characteristics and clarified the RX leakage specification with an additional note. Noted that the sensitivity levels are with respect to a QFN device and a small reduction in sensitivity will occur when using a CSP device.
Changed the minimum range of the RSSI from –100 dBm to RX sensitivity +3 dB. Changed RSSI accuracy to ±6 dB. Removed RSSI resolution. For more information, see RF RX Performance Characteristics.
Added ACR and co-channel rejection to RF RX Performance Characteristics.

Added two TX programmable power ranges to the RF TX Performance Characteristics table. Noted that an external RF output filter will not impact output power, but may increase the TX current consumption by 300 µA in non-buck mode. Also updated second and third harmonic levels at 0dBm with VDDPA = 0.92 V.
Bifurcated the battery measurement accuracy across two supply ranges in General-Purpose 12-Bit ADC Characteristics with new accuracy ranges.
Updated THD+N values in High-Fidelity ADC Characteristics.
Changed incorrect units from ms to µs for PLL lock time in the Audio PLL Characteristics table and updated the current consumption values.
Updated the 32 MHz crystal oscillator frequency trim range from ±30 ppm to -27/+33 ppm in 32 MHz Crystal Oscillator Operating Conditions and Characteristics.
Changed the minimum regulator voltage from 0.89 V to 0.88 V in the Power Management Characteristics table.
Added low power LDO supply range and increased boost converter efficiency in the Power Management Characteristics table.
Updated the TX mode current consumption from 6.85 mA to 6.52 mA and updated the advertising currents in Low Supply Mode Current Consumption Characteristics.
Added LS device sleep currents to System Sleep Mode Current Consumption Characteristics.
Added LS device deep sleep currents to System Deep Sleep Mode Current Consumption Characteristics.
Updated timing information in SPI2AHB Slave Timing and I2S Master Timing.
Added the following timing sections: I2S Slave Timing, SPI Master Timing, SPI Slave Timing, UART Timing, I2C Timing, 2-Wire JTAG Timing, and 4-Wire JTAG Timing.
Changed the analog IO descriptions in the Pin Descriptions section to state that the IO should be left to float when the pins are not used.
Updated the General Purpose IO (GPIO) Default Configurations description.
Corrected CSP package X and Y dimensions from 3134 µm × 3278 µm to 3156 µm × 3298 µm in Package Specification.
Updated the Ordering Information table.

topic.title: Revision 4.0

body.p: Revision 4.0 was published in March 2019. The following is a summary of changes.

li.p: Updated block diagram in Product Overview.
Updated HB_WS buck mode, HB_WS non-buck mode, and HB_LS block diagrams in Functional Descriptions to include optional 32.768 kHz crystal, showing C4 and the harmonic filter as optional.
Updated External Components to include Y2 and the missing C6.
Removed 9-bit serial data support from UART section Peripherals, as it was mistakenly included.
Updated figure 8 in Peripherals for clarity and added flash erase-program endurance minimum cycles to the flash section.
Added or updated all specification symbols on all tables.
Added analog IO voltage range maximum to Absolute Maximum Ratings.
Updated battery supply range with buck minimum from 1.5 V to 1.8 V in Recommended Operating Conditions for HB_WS to be consistent with other entries.
Updated improved RX sensitivity for all modes in RF RX Performance Characteristics and updated note 1 to show increase in current from 400 uA to 900 uA when using enhanced gain mode.
Updated RSSI range, accuracy, and resolution numbers in RF RX Performance Characteristics.
Split out TX output power at 0 dBm separately for LS/WS non buck mode and WS buck mode in RF TX Performance Characteristics, and updated note 1.
Added battery measurement and temperature measurement accuracy to High-Fidelity ADC Characteristics.

Lowered the minimum of the audio PLL output frequency range to 32.256 MHz from 45.1584 MHz, added output frequency trim range, and added current consumption at 32.256 MHz to Audio PLL Characteristics.
Changed the 32 MHz crystal maximum ESR specification from 80 Ω to 50 Ω and typical from 35 Ω to 25 Ω in 32 MHz Crystal Oscillator Operating Conditions and Characteristics.
Removed the current consumption of the 32 MHz crystal oscillator from 32 MHz Crystal Oscillator Operating Conditions and Characteristics.

Removed the current consumption of the 32 kHz crystal oscillator from 32 kHz Crystal Oscillator Operating Conditions and Characteristics, as it has been moved to System Deep Sleep Mode Current Consumption Characteristics.
Removed the current consumption of the 32 kHz RC oscillator from 32 kHz RC Oscillator Characteristics, as it has been moved to System Deep Sleep Mode Current Consumption Characteristics.
Changed the battery voltage reference from 2.8 V to 3.0 V in Power Management Characteristics, and also updated the typical buck efficiency at 5 mA load to 84% from 81%.
Added I2S Timing section.
Updated non-buck VBATT voltage threshold from 0.975 V typical to 1 V typical in Supply Monitoring Operating Conditions and Characteristics, and included typical values into table.
Removed dynamic GPIO characteristics from General Purpose IO (GPIO) Default Configurations, as these characteristics will now be contained in separate peripherals sections.

Added current consumption for 5-second advertising when using the RC oscillator to table Buck Mode Current Consumption Characteristics. Also updated the current consumption with 3 dBm output power and 5-second advertising from 1200 nA to 1300 nA, and added flash page erase and write current consumption to the table. Also added RX current consumption for 2 Mbps, S2 and S8 modes.
Corrected the maximum voltage for non-buck mode operation from 1.5 V to 2.5 V in table Non-Buck Mode Current Consumption Characteristics.

Added current consumption for 5-second advertising when using the RC oscillator to table Non-Buck Mode Current Consumption Characteristics. Also updated the current consumption with 0 dBm output power and 5-second advertising with external 32.768 kHz clock from 1650 nA to 1850 nA and added flash page erase and write current consumption to the table. Also added RX current consumption for 2 Mbps, S2 and S8 modes and updated 1 Mbps RX current from 4.9 mA to 5.0 mA.

Added current consumption for 5-second advertising when using the RC oscillator to table Low Supply Mode Current Consumption Characteristics. Also added flash page erase and write current consumption to the table and updated the current consumption with Pout = 0 dBm from 6.75 mA to 6.85 mA, and RX mode current for 1 Mbps mode from 4.95 mA to 5.15 mA. Also added RX current consumption for 2 Mbps, S2 and S8 modes.
Updated the reference VBATT voltage from 2.8 V to 3.0 V for both System Sleep Mode Current Consumption Characteristics and System Deep Sleep Mode Current Consumption Characteristics.

Added deep sleep current with 32.768 kHz crystal oscillator running to System Deep Sleep Mode Current Consumption Characteristics. Also updated the deep sleep current with RC oscillator running from 250 nA to 280 nA, and deep sleep current with external clock from 160 nA to 185 nA.
Added a SPI2AHB slave timing characteristics section in SPI2AHB Slave Timing.

Added clarification note for WUP_EN pin in Pin Descriptions that this input is used in conjunction with RESET_B to invoke Service mode. Added clarification note on VSUP pin to connect to external capacitor or VBATT, depending on whether buck mode or non-buck mode is required. Added note that if VSW pin is not needed then leave unconnected.
Updated the General Purpose IO (GPIO) Default Configurations description.
Updated the Ordering Information table.

topic.title: Low-Supply Mode

body.p: The low-supply HB20 variant (HB_LS) is used to facilitate use of a single low-supply range of 0.92 V to 1.8 V, ideal for supporting applications running from zinc air, AA, or AAA batteries. In this configuration, an internal boost converter is used to supply the internal flash supply voltage and VDDIO is provided directly from the battery. Please note that if a VDDIO voltage above 1.62 V is available, then the standard HB20 device HB_WS is recommended instead.
For more information on the harmonic filter, see RF TX Performance Characteristics.

topic.title: CPU Complex

body.p: The CPU complex has two identical Synopsys ARC® EM11D1 digital signal processor (DSP) cores. The only difference between the two cores is the size of the data closely coupled memory (DCCM) static random access memory (SRAM). Core 0 has a total of 56 KB of usable DCCM SRAM while core 1 has a total of 152 KB of usable DCCM SRAM.

The ARC-EM11D DSP is optimized for use in low-power embedded applications where DSP performance and low power consumption are required. Typical always-on applications such as those in the Internet of Things (IoT) market need this combination of features to enable optimum device performance and extended battery life. The ARC-EM11D has a 16 KB, two-way instruction cache. It also supports multibanked memories (called XY) to vastly improve multiply and accumulate (MAC)/cycle performance and lower energy consumption, with support for two 16×16 MAC/cycle or one 32×32 MAC/cycle.
1 ARC is a registered trademark of Synopsys.

body.p: ARConnect is a collection of system components that provides efficient inter-core communications, interrupt distribution, debug assistance, and other inter-core functionality in a multicore system. topic.title: Interrupt Architecture

body.p: The ARC-EM11D interrupt unit handles interrupts from the timers, DMAs, MCIP, and external interrupt inputs. External interrupts are synchronized to the internal clock and are individually programmable as pulse- or level-sensitive. The interrupt unit supports up to eight priority levels.

topic.title: Timers

body.p: The following timers are in the ARC-EM11D core:

li.p: Timer0
Timer1
Real-time counter (RTC)
Watchdog timer

body.p: The processor timers are two independent 32-bit timers (timer0 and timer1) and a 64-bit real-time counter. Timer0 and timer1 are identical in operation, except that they are connected to different interrupts. The processor timers are connected to the system clock signal, which operates even when the ARC-EM11D processor is in the sleep state. The timers can be used to generate interrupt signals that wake the processor from the sleep state.

topic.title: Watchdog Timer

body.p: The processor should periodically write a preset password to reset the watchdog timer to start counting from the preset start value. If the ARC-EM11D processor fails to write the preset password, the watchdog timer counter counts down to zero. By writing the password periodically, the ARC-EM11D processor indicates that it has not run into any timing-related errors.

User-programmable prioritization scheme for all channels
Concurrent operation with the CPU
Software- and hardware-triggered DMA transfers
Two addressing modes
Up to five data transfer modes
Internal and external interrupt support
Demand-driven DMA

topic.title: XY Memory Interface

body.p: XY memory is a feature commonly found in DSP processors to increase the DSP performance. The XY component allows the ARC-EM11D processor to implicitly load source operands and store results into a closely coupled memory (CCM) using a single instruction. This results in dense code and high performance. XY memory is accessed through a set of address pointers and modifiers in the address generation unit (AGU). Modifiers define the data type and increment values for the XY address pointers in the AGU. For the ARC-EM11D cores, X memory is often denoted as XCCM, and Y memory is often denoted as YCCM.
Using the XY memory architecture allows a single ARC-EM11D instruction to perform all the following manipulations in a single clock cycle:

li.p: Load two source operands (one from X memory and one from Y memory) from XY memory by dereferencing address pointers
Post-increment the address pointers
Compute the result of the instruction (multiply the operands, MAC the operands, and so on)
Write back the result to XY memory by dereferencing an address pointer
Post-increment the destination address pointer

body.p: The ARC-EM11D memory-protection feature includes:

Code protection: Hardware to block read and write to code space

topic.title: Performance Counters

body.p: The ARC-EM11D core includes a performance-monitoring system that enables rapid optimization of the ARC-based systems. The performance-monitoring system helps to improve optimization techniques and can be used for the following:

li.p: Hot-spot analysis: Locates the functions and instructions consuming the most CPU time.

Hardware-assisted statistical code profiling: Provides visibility of instruction-execution frequencies. The system can also capture micro-architecture detail, revealing the average time taken for each instruction and allowing root causes of instruction stalls and pipeline flushes to be identified. The performance monitor collects data from unmodified code with minimal impact on system performance.

Instruction flow metrics: Identify patterns of behavior common to the whole system. An insight into the behavior of the system as a whole can be gained without requiring knowledge of any individual program block. System-level metrics are calculated from hardware counts of instruction and pipeline events. Example metrics include the following:
Instructions per clock (IPC)
Cache-miss rates
Branch-prediction accuracy
Average load-use penalty
Breakdown of stall causes
Instruction mix (LD, ST, branch, and so on)
Instruction size (16 bits or 32 bits)
Average function size
Average instructions between branches
Time spent in interrupt or exception handlers
Measurements of minimum, maximum, and average response times

body.p: Analysis of metrics can highlight techniques for improvement in the program code, compiler configuration, memory-subsystem design, and CPU configuration.

Core registers

topic.title: Actionpoints

body.p: The actionpoint system is used for enhanced debugging of application software in real time. The actionpoints mechanism supports breakpoints and watchpoints. A breakpoint is an actionpoint that triggers on a specific instruction, or range of instructions, being executed. A watchpoint is an actionpoint that detects specific address or data values being accessed by memory-referencing instructions, auxiliary register read (LR) and write (SR) instructions, or the presence of specific values on the two optional external parameter ports.

body.p: PUF provides secure key storage without storing the key. This is done by using a device's digital fingerprint as derived from SRAM. Instead of storing the key, a key code is generated, which in combination with the digital fingerprint is used to reconstruct keys to be used by the customer’s client design.

li.p: Key strength of 256 bits
Generation, storage, and reconstruction of intrinsic keys
Storage and reconstruction of user keys
Key sizes from 64 bits to 4096 bits
Embedded true random number generation (256 bits)

topic.title: Inter-Integrated Circuit (I2C)

body.p: The I2C bus is a two-wire serial interface, consisting of a serial data line (SDA) and a serial clock (SCL). These wires carry information between the devices connected to the bus. Each device is recognized by a unique address and can operate as either a transmitter or receiver, depending on the function of the device. Devices can also be considered as masters or slaves when performing data transfers. A master is a device that initiates a data transfer on the bus and generates the clock signals to permit that transfer. At that time, any device addressed is considered a slave.
I2C has the following features:

li.p: Two speeds
Standard mode (0 to 100 kbps)
Fast mode (less than or equal to 400 kbps)
Clock synchronization
Master or slave I2C operation
7- or 10-bit addressing
7- or 10-bit combined format transfers

topic.title: Inter-IC Sound (I2S) Master/Slave

body.p: The I2S master/slave are two separate blocks. The I2S master drives serial clock (sclk) and word select (ws) out while the I2S slave receives both. The I2S bus is a simple three-wire serial bus protocol developed by Philips to transfer stereo audio data. The bus handles only the transfer of audio data; hence, control and subcoding signals need to be transferred separately using a different bus protocol (such as I2C).
The I2S blocks have the following features:

li.p: I2S transmitter and/or receiver based on the Philips I2S serial protocol
Configurable number of stereo channels (up to four) for both transmitter and receiver
Full-duplex communication due to the independence of transmitter and receiver
Asynchronous clocking of Advanced Peripheral Bus (APB) and I2S sclk
Sample rates of 16, 24, 32, 44.1, 48, and 96 ksps supported
Audio data resolutions of 12, 16, 20, 24, and 32 bits
I2S clock rates of up to 6.144 MHz supported (32-bit left and right channels at 96 ksps)
External sclk gating and enable signals
First-in, first-out (FIFO) depth of eight words
Configurable support for programmable DMA registers
Programmable FIFO thresholds
Master/slave operation

topic.title: SPI Master/Slave

body.p: The SPI master/slave are two separate blocks. The SPI master is a full-duplex serial interface and supports up to four slave chip selects. The host processor accesses data, control, and status information through the APB interface. The SPI may also interface with a DMA controller using an optional set of DMA signals, which can be selected at configuration time. The SPI slave is a synchronous interface and is internally sampled by the internal clock. The maximum clock rate for the SPI slave and master is 8 MHz.
The SPI master/slave can connect to any serial-slave peripheral device using the following interface:

li.p: Motorola serial peripheral interface (SPI): A four-wire, full-duplex serial protocol from Motorola

body.p: There are four possible combinations for the serial clock phase and polarity.

topic.title: Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC) Controller

body.p: The ADC controller receives and buffers ADC data from the three ADC blocks (ADC0, ADC1, and ADC2), which in turn have access to the four analog input ports PIOA0 to PIOA3. The digital buffers are implemented as 24-bit-wide and 8-word-deep FIFOs. The data is sampled and written to the corresponding FIFO. The ADC data stored in the FIFOs can be DMAed to the DSP core memories for data processing. The processed data can be forwarded to the Bluetooth Low-Energy radio, I2S, and other peripheral interfaces.
The ADC controller operates in continuous sampling mode on a single input channel at rates up to 125 ksps, or it can operate directly under CPU control in incremental mode up to 7.6 ksps.

ADC2 includes a six-way input multiplexer that may be used to measure signals from the four analog input ports, plus battery level and temperature sensor signals. ADC2 may also be used in conjunction with the ADC controller sequencer mode to automatically sample the six analog input channels in a predetermined sequence and rate. Inputs can be saved in the FIFO along with a port ID to identify the source.

The ADC controller outputs FIFO Ready and FIFO Almost Full signals from each FIFO. These signals may be routed to the DMA controller to automatically buffer data samples into main memory without CPU intervention.

topic.title: Always-On (AON) Watchdog Timer

body.p: The AON watchdog timer runs directly off the battery and counts 32.768 kHz clock periods when the HB20 CPU cores are booted. The watchdog has two modes of operation. In the default mode of operation, the watchdog creates an interrupt when the timer reaches the default limit. Alternatively, the watchdog issues a full system reset if an AON register bit is set to 1 (default is 0).

topic.title: Flash

body.p: The flash contains 512 KB of programmable memory and 3 × 8 KB information pages for general use. It also contains 1 × 8 KB of manufacturing information which cannot be programmed. The CPUs may execute directly from the flash using their cache controllers.

The flash may be programmed from the SPI2AHB, JTAG7, over-the-air (OTA), or UART bootloader. The CPUs may also program a page of the flash while executing out of other pages for over-the-air updates. Up to 10,000 erase-program cycles are permitted. The flash may be erased one 8 KB page at a time.
The user may program IO port protection in the flash to prevent access to the flash or to other parts of the device from various external sources and also disable service mode operation.
Flash data contains error correction coding (ECC). Single-bit errors in 2 × 32 bit words can be detected and corrected, and double-bit errors can be detected.

body.p: The DesignWare GPIO allows for parallel word data to be routed to GPIO pins. It also allows for edge detection of GPIO input pins and sending an interrupt to the processor. topic.title: Supply Monitoring

body.p: The supply monitoring circuitry is enabled on each start-up sequence and monitors the VBATT, VSUP, and internal VDDIO_FLASH voltages. Detection of a supply voltage below a predetermined threshold leads to either a CPU interrupt (default) or system reset, depending on the configuration set by the user. The threshold detection levels are given in the table Supply Monitoring Operating Conditions and Characteristics. The supply monitoring circuitry may also be used to detect brown-out events that meet the temporal mask requirements given in the figure Brown-Out Event Mask with the associated minimum timings given in the table Supply Monitoring Operating Conditions and Characteristics.
The following illustration shows the brown-out event mask.

topic.title: Service Mode

body.p: In service mode, the HB20 device does not run the application contained in flash. Instead, it automatically enables (connects) the GPIO inputs for the SPI2AHB, JTAG7, and UART0 interfaces so they can be used to access the device and program an application into the flash, if desired. For more information regarding the GPIO in service mode, see General-Purpose IO (GPIO) Default Configurations .
Note that for security reasons, service mode is intended to be used only during development, and can be disabled during production of an end product.

Service mode is invoked by holding WUP_EN high for at least tPR1 or tPR2 after RESET_B is toggled low or after applying VBATT voltage, which causes the POR to operate. Please refer to table Supply Ramp Up Time Requirements and Processor Start-Up Time Characteristics for the timing requirements of tPR1 or tPR2.

topic.title: System Sleep Mode Current Consumption (RAM Retention Mode)

body.p: System sleep mode is used to place the HB20 device into a low-power state between connection events. During system sleep mode, the buck and main LDOs are powered down and a low-power LDO is enabled to supply a constant voltage for 8 KB of internal retention RAM in core 0 and/or core 1. A low-power RC oscillator/crystal oscillator or external oscillator may be used to wake up the HB20 device for connection events. The HB20 device may also be woken up from sleep by toggling the wake-up enable pin (WUP_EN) without the need for internal clocks running.
Total current consumption is measured on VBATT and VDDIO.

topic.title: System Deep-Sleep Mode Current Consumption

body.p: System deep-sleep mode is used by the HB20 device to save power between advertising events. In deep-sleep mode, the core LDOs and retention RAM are powered off while the registers in the always-on section are left powered up. Up to 25 bytes of always-on registers are available for use during deep-sleep mode. A low-power RC oscillator/crystal oscillator or external oscillator may be used to wake up the HB20 device for advertising events. The HB20 device may also be woken up from deep sleep by toggling the wake-up enable pin (WUP_EN) without the need for internal clocks running.
Total current consumption is measured on VBATT and VDDIO.

topic.title: General-Purpose IO (GPIO) Default Configurations

body.p: On application of the VBATT voltage or a system reset, the GPIO pins are configured with default signal selections, pull-ups, and pull-downs as shown in GPIO Default Pin Configurations, but are all tri-stated to prevent contention in case the application uses the pins for something other than the defaults. The HB20 device then either enters service mode (see Service Mode), or runs the application in flash.

If the HB20 device enters service mode, then it automatically enables (connects) the inputs for the SPI2AHB, JTAG7, and UART0 interfaces so they can be used to access the device and program an application into the flash, if desired. For each of these interfaces, the device automatically enables (drives) the interface's output pins as appropriate, which occurs only if the interface's inputs are used to access the device. This prevents contention in case the application uses the same pins for something else.

If the HB20 device runs the application in flash, then the application must configure the GPIO signal selections, pull-ups, and pull-downs as required by the application, and then enable the selected inputs to connect the corresponding pins to the selected input signals. For the selected output signals, the device automatically enables (drives) the output pins only as appropriate.
Note the following:

li.p: The JTAG7 signals are the user debug interface for the CPU core(s). The other JTAG signals are for internal factory use only.

If a valid UART0_RX input signal is detected on GPIO_0, then the HB20 device automatically changes the signal selected for GPIO_1 to UART0_TX and enables (drives) the output. Otherwise GPIO_1 remains tri-stated with O_JTAG_TDO selected. A valid UART0_RX signal consists of three key presses (space bar and/or Enter keys) at baud 115200 (8N1).
